cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this framework, please cite it as below."
type: software
title: "Principles of Earned Autonomy: A Governance Framework for Autonomous Agents"
abstract: >
  Proposed theory-level governance framework for how autonomous AI agents may
  earn and exercise authority. The claimed contribution is a synthesis rather
  than a standalone novelty: two core problems (autonomous reasoning and earned
  autonomy), three architectural principles (Commander's Intent, Observable
  Autonomy, Convergence Is Silence), and one proposed measurable property
  (Autonomous Reasoning Fidelity, ARF) are combined into a discipline of earned,
  observable, revocable authority. ARF is operationally defined with technique
  ancestry (Winograd Schema Challenge, CheckList, Lanham et al. 2023 on CoT
  faithfulness), a defined contrastive-pair probe structure, a falsifiable
  claim, and a formalization agenda. Includes conformance tests for all three
  principles and for ARF, plus bounded reference evidence from two separately
  published reference implementations: (A) the Principles of Earned Autonomy
  Skills Suite (a three-family, single-operator-administered silence-convergence
  run across Anthropic, xAI/Grok, and Google/Gemini, anchored to a public
  append-only audit trail), and (B) the LLM Harness Protocol (a transparent
  MITM proxy that writes a tamper-evident, hash-chained, append-only ledger of
  every LLM interaction before the response is released to the caller, across
  OpenAI, Anthropic, and Gemini APIs). Implementation A documents falsification
  findings that bound the convergence claim; Implementation B demonstrates that
  capture-author separation - the structural property Principle 2 requires - is
  buildable in current tooling. A formal References section with full
  bibliographic entries grounds every inline citation. Presented as a step
  toward deployable governance for delegability, not as a complete solution to
  AI safety or autonomy. Implementation-agnostic.
